			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Games do <em>not</em> run from $8000; they run from whatever address appears in $FFFC-$FFFD.</div><br /><br />Ahh.. thanks for setting me straight, and for that trampoline.  I knew I had to be missing something in there.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And would your menu cart use the first cart's lockout chip?</div><br /><br />I don't see why not.  After all, the quickest way to a prototype is to hack an existing cart anyway, so I might as well keep the CIC on there while I'm at it.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And how would you (cleanly) make the latch disappear from the bus as soon as it is written to once?</div>
<br />
<br />Good point.  You wouldn't want any given cart tripping over the latch during gameplay.
<br />
<br />I was thinking about setting the enable line of the latch to be a logical AND of whatever address lines its mapped to AND NOT the OR all of the output latch lines.  This way, it'll disable itself once the decoder is set to something other than zero, making it a one-shot deal.
<br />
<br />Latch Logic 'pseudocode' (since I can't draw a decent schematic here):
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">latchWriteEnable = &#40;A15 &amp; A14 &amp; A13 &amp; A12&#41; &amp; !&#40;Y0 | Y1 | Y2 | Y3 ... Yn&#41;</div>
<br />
<br />Where Y0..Yn are the decoded outputs of the latch, and A15..A12 are the most significant address lines on the NES PRG bus ($Fxxx mapping).
<br />
<br />I haven't breadboarded this yet, but I don't see why it wouldn't work.</div>

