						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well I've never built anything like this, I just have the designs in my head, heheh.</div><br /><br />Well, as usual, it seems that I'm in good company. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I was looking at using the 74HCT245 for a similar use.  Have something like that for every data bus of every slot (using the read/write signal to select the direction), and possibly another similar chip that's not bidirectional (if it's cheaper or whatever) for all the address and control signals.</div><br /><br />Awesome.  Thanks for all this wonderful info - its tough to find this stuff out elsewhere.  After reading the spec sheet, it's very clear to me now.<br /><br />So now I see where you're going with this.  The "bus transceiver" has a bona-fide "off" state - that should guard the cartridge circuitry nicely when coupled with the master latch.  <br /><br />Also, the chip count for this beast is starting to rise exponentally.  I'm starting to see why you were imagining an external power source to go with this.  Still, with only driving power to one cart at at time, how much of a drain do you think all these extra chips will cause?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Just copy the code into RAM, and run it from there.  Kinda like bankswitching, but more like cartswitching, heheh.</div>
<br />
<br />"Cartswitching" - I like the sound of that.  That's pretty much what I'm trying to design.
<br />
<br />Edit:  The chip listing on the M82 page shows how close to the mark Memblers is:
<br />
<br />74-series ICs on the main board:
<br />ALS245 x 7
<br />HCT541 x 8
<br />ALS251 x 4
<br />HCT4514 x 1
<br />HCT373 x 2
<br />HCT540  x 2
<br />HCT139 x 2
<br />HC04 x 2
<br />HCT08 x 2
<br />
<br />Scary.</div>

